text:
A standard barrel can fill 225 liters, the equivalent of 300 bottles, or 25 cases of 12 bottles. This barrel is the one used in wineries in most parts of the world. New wood gives the wine an oaky aroma and flavour, and this is usually present with a vanilla flavour or a smoky character, as well as wood tannins. This effect diminishes as the barrel ages, so a one-year-old barrel will give less flavor than a new one. By the time a barrel reaches its fourth year, it will impart little flavor and tannin to the wine. Below is a descending scale of the contribution of the barrels as they age:

Small new oak barrels;

Second-hand oak barrels (one or two years old);

Old large barrels and tanks;

Neutral tanks: stainless steel, epoxy, glass coated.

Typically a barrel-aged red wine will remain in the barrel for a maximum of 18 months to two years before bottling, although there are some, such as Barolo, that will remain in the barrel for longer.
